-------------------------------------------------------------------- Lacture 138

AWS Global Infrastructure

A global application is an application deployed in multiple geographies
On AWS: this could be Regions and / or Edge Locations

Regions
Availablity zones
edge location (point of presence)

Why make a global application?
    Decreased Latency and better experience
    Disaster Recovery (DR)
    Attack protection: distributed global infrastructure is harder to attack

Amazon Route 53
    Route53 is a Managed DNS (Domain Name System)

Route 53 Routing Policies
    SIMPLE ROUTING POLICY (No health checks)
    WEIGHTED ROUTING POLICY
    LATENCY ROUTING POLICY
    FAILOVER ROUTING POLICY (Disaster Recovery)

Route 53 hands on (cost money)

Amazon CloudFront
    Content Delivery Network (CDN)
    Improves read performance, content is cached at the edge
    Improves users experience
    Many Points of Presence globally (Edge Locations, Edge Caches…)
    DDoS protection (because worldwide), integration with Shield, AWS Web Application Firewall

CloudFront – Origins
• S3 bucket
• VPC Origin
• Custom Origin (HTTP)

CloudFront hands on
    access private s3 bucket data from cloudfront origins


AWS Global Accelerator
    Improve global application availability and performance using the AWS global network
    Leverage the AWS internal network to optimize the route to your application (60% improvement)
    2 Anycast IP are created for your application and traffic is sent through Edge Locations
    The Edge locations send the traffic to your application

S3 Transfer Acceleration 
    To connet to s3 bucket first connect to an edge location then aws speedup edge location - s3 bucket 


AWS Outposts 
    to fasilate Hybrid Cloud management
    AWS Outposts are “server racks” that offers the same AWS infrastructure, services, APIs & tools on-premise
    AWS will setup and manage “Outposts Racks” within your on - premises infrastructure
    You are responsible for the Outposts Rack physical security

AWS WaveLength
    WaveLength Zones are infrastructure deployments embedded within the telecommunications providers’ datacenters 
    Brings AWS services to the edge of the 5G networks (which enable Ultra-low latency applications)
    Traffic doesn’t leave the Communication Service Provider’s (CSP) network
    Use cases: Smart Cities, ML-assisted diagnostics, Connected Vehicles, Interactive Live Video Streams, AR/VR, 

AWS Local Zones - Extension of an AWS Region
    to run latency-sensitive applications
    Places AWS compute, storage, database, and other selected AWS services closer to end users 
    Compatible with EC2, RDS, ECS, EBS, ElastiCache, Direct Connect

Global Applications Architecture:

    Single Region - Single AZ
        Availability    - low
        Global Latency  - high
        Difficulty      - low

    Single Region - Multi AZ
        Availability    - higher than Single AZ
        Global Latency  - lower than Single AZ
        Difficulty      - higher than Single AZ

    Multi Region, Active-Passive (read from multiple AZ but write to only one AZ)
        Availability    - higher than Single Region
        Global Latency  - lower than Single Region
        Difficulty      - higher than Single Region

    Multi Region, Active-Active (real and write to all AZ)
        Availability    - higest
        Global Latency  - lowest
        Difficulty      - higest


