-------------------------------------------------------------------- Lacture 183

SECURITY AND COMPLIANCE SECTION


AWS Shared Responsibility Model


DDOS (Distributed Denial-of-Service) Attack Protection on AWS
    AWS Shield Standard (FREE): protects against DDOS attack for your website and applications
    AWS Shield Advanced (PAID): 24/7 premium DDoS protection
    AWS WAF: Filter specific requests based on rules
    CloudFront and Route 53: 
        Availability protection using global edge network 
        Combined with AWS Shield, provides attack mitigation at the edge
    Be ready to scale – leverage AWS Auto Scaling


AWS Shield
    AWS Shield Standard: (FREE)
        Provides protection from attacks such as SYN/UDP Floods, Reflection attacks and other layer 3 or 4 attacks
    AWS Shield Advanced: (PAID)
        Protect against more sophisticated attack on Amazon servive like 
            EC2
            Elastic Load Balancing (ELB)
            Amazon CloudFront
            AWS Global Accelerator
            Route 53
        24/7 access to AWS DDoS response team (DRP)
        Protect against higher fees during usage spikes due to DDoS


AWS WAF – Web Application Firewall
    Protects from Layer 7 (HTTP) attack
    Deploy on Application Load Balancer, API Gateway, CloudFront
    Define Web ACL (Web Access Control List):
    Rules can include IP addresses, HTTP headers, HTTP body, or URI strings
    Protects from common attack - SQL injection and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
    Size constraints, geo-match (block countries)
    Rate-based rules (to count occurrences of events) – for DDoS protection


AWS Network Firewall (Protect Amazon VPC)
    From Layer 3 to Layer 7 protection
    Any direction, you can inspect
        VPC to VPC traffic
        Outbound to internet
        Inbound from internet
        To / from Direct Connect & Site-to-Site VPN


AWS Firewall Manager
    Firewall Manager = External defense (network & perimeter security)
    Manage security rules in all accounts of an Organization using AWS
    Security policy: common set of security rules
        VPC Security Groups for EC2, Application Load Balancer, etc…
        WAF rules
        AWS Shield Advanced
        AWS Network Firewall
    Rules are applied to resources and accounts (in present and create in future) in your Organization


Penetration Testing on AWS Cloud
    AWS customers can carry out security assessments or penetration tests against their AWS infrastructure
    not need of prior approval for mentioned services (like EC2 instances, RDS, Lambda, etc)
    Penetration testing are not allowed for many service
        DNS zone walking via Amazon Route 53 Hosted Zones, DDoS and DoS etc are prohibited


AWS KMS (Key Management Service)
    Anytime you hear “encryption” for an AWS service, it’s most likely KMS
    AWS manages the encryption keys for us
        Encryption Opt-in: EBS volumes, S3 buckets, Redshift database, RDS database, EFS drives
        Encryption Automatically enabled: CloudTrail Logs, S3 Glacier, Storage Gateway

KMS Hands On


CloudHSM (HSM = Hardware Security Module)
    AWS provisions encryption hardware (tamper resistant, FIPS 140 -2 Level 3 compliance)
    You manage your own encryption keys entirely (not AWS)
    AWS only manage Encription Hardware


Types of KMS Keys
    Customer Managed Key (CMK)  - Created, managed and used by customer
    AWS Managed Key             - Created, managed and used on the customer’s behalf by AWS
    AWS Owned Key               - Collection of CMKs owns and manages by AWS to use in multiple accounts
    CloudHSM Keys               - Generated from your own CloudHSM


AWS Certificate Manager (ACM)
    provision, manage, and deploy SSL/TLS (Secure Sockets Layer / Transport Layer Security)) Certificates
    Used to provide in-flight encryption for websites (HTTPS)
    Supports both public and private TLS certificates
    Free for public TLS certificates
    Integrations with (load TLS certificates on)
        Elastic Load Balancers
        CloudFront Distributions
        APIs on API Gateway


AWS Secrets Manager
    Service for storing secrets
    Capability to force rotation of secrets every X days (Automate generation secrets on rotation)
    Integration with Amazon RDS (MySQL, PostgreSQL, Aurora)
    Secrets are encrypted using KMS


AWS Artifact (not really a service)
    Portal that provides cx with on-demand access to AWS compliance documentation and AWS agreements
    Can be used to support internal audit or compliance


Amazon GuardDuty
    GuardDuty CHECK LOGS to find security check
    Intelligent Threat discovery to protect your AWS Account
    Uses Machine Learning algorithms, anomaly detection, 3rd party data
    Input data to find anamolies (Unusual activity)
        DNS Logs 
        VPC Flow Logs 
        CloudTrail Events Logs – use CloudTrail Management Events and S3 Data Events 
    Can setup EventBridge rules to be notified with SNS or target AWS Lambda (in case of findings)
    Can protect against CryptoCurrency attacks (has a dedicated “finding” for it)


Amazon Inspector
    Inspector CHECK COMPUTATIONAL RESOURCES to find security check
    Automated Security Assessments For EC2 INSTANCES, LAMBDA FUNCTIONS AND CONTAINER IMAGES PUSH TO AMAZON ECR
    Reporting & integration with AWS Security Hub
    Send findings to Amazon Event Bridge
    For EC2 instances
        Leveraging the AWS System Manager (SSM) agent
        Analyze unintended network accessibility and OS against known vulnerabilities
    For Container Images push to Amazon ECR
        Assessment of Container Images as they are pushed
    For Lambda Functions
        Identifies software vulnerabilities in function code and package dependencies
        Assessment of functions as they are deployed


AWS Config (Paid Service)
    Auditing and recording CONFIGURATION COMPLIANCE of your AWS resources
    Record configurations and changes over time
    Can receive alerts (SNS notifications) for any changes
    AWS Config is a per-region service but Can be aggregated across regions and accounts
    Questions that can be solved by AWS Config:
        Is there unrestricted SSH access to my security groups?
        Do my buckets have any public access?
        How has my ALB configuration changed over time?


AWS Macie
    Use to Identify PERSONALLY IDENTIFIABLE INFORMATION (PII)
    Amazon Macie is a fully managed data security and data privacy service
    uses machine learning and pattern matching to discover and protect your sensitive data in AWS.
    identify and alert you to sensitive data, such as personally identifiable information (PII)


AWS Security Hub
    Security Hub = Internal defense (visibility, monitoring, compliance)
    Central security tool to manage security across several AWS accounts and automate security checks
    Integrated dashboards showing current security and compliance status to quickly take actions
    Automatically aggregates alerts from various AWS services & partner tools:
        like Config, GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, IAM Access Analyzer, AWS Firewall Manager, etc


Amazon Detective
    Use to find the ROOT CAUSE of security Loopholes
    GuardDuty, Macie, and Security Hub are used to identify potential security issues, or findings
    Sometimes security findings require deeper analysis to isolate the root cause and take action
    Analyzes, investigates, and quickly identifies the root cause 
    use ML and graphs to find root cause of security issues or suspicious activities 
    Automatically collects and processes events from VPC Flow Logs, CloudTrail, GuardDuty
    Produces visualizations with details and context to get to the root cause


AWS Abuse
    Report suspected AWS resources used for abusive or illegal purposes
    Abusive & prohibited behaviors are:
        Port scanning
        DoS or DDoS attacks – by AWS-owned IP 
        Spam – receving undesired spam from AWS
        Distributing malware – use AWS resources
        Hosting objectionable or copyrighted content
        Intrusion attempts – logging in on your resources


Root user privileges
    LOCK AWAY YOUR AWS ACCOUNT ROOT USER ACCESS KEYS!
    Actions that can be performed only by the root user:
        CHANGE ACCOUNT SETTINGS (account name, email address, root user password, root user access keys)
        CLOSE YOUR AWS ACCOUNT
        CHANGE OR CANCEL YOUR AWS SUPPORT PLAN
        REGISTER AS A SELLER IN THE RESERVED INSTANCE MARKETPLACE
        View certain tax invoices
        Restore IAM user permissions
        Configure an Amazon S3 bucket to enable MFA
        Edit or delete an Amazon S3 bucket policy that includes an invalid VPC ID or VPC endpoint ID
        Sign up for GovCloud


IAM Access Analyzer
    Find out which resources are shared externally
        like S3 Buckets, IAM Roles, KMS Keys, Lambda Functions, SQS queues, Secrets Manager Secrets
    Define Zone of Trust = AWS Account or AWS Organization
    Access outside zone of trusts => findings


